The interview - Sangre becomes safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated his 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has again become one of the safest and most effective providers of blood in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that he had been seriously wavered by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the discontent of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster would no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, some provinces then created a committee that aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau committee accomplished this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gelineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, he recalls Descary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence - it says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population in Quebec had the successive confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, remembers that confidence is extremely fragile.
Since its inception, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the disease of the crazy cow, a new variant of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, Count Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gelineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we set out exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. —
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: Nucleus acid tests that enable the blood of donors to detect the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, which were based on the tests used so far.
Nucleid acid tests made it possible to shorten the period between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period within a period of less than one week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements resulted in a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS for a blood transfusion.
Today, every 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
This means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think it is possible to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion today to recover health without any worries, says the head of Hema-Québec's management.
Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, for example, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant - Dr. Décary goes on to point out that, in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since more aggressive anticancer treatments, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet injection.
Ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regroups on average only 3% of Quebecs eligible for blood donation.
All people with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 % of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all, to retain and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate his blood - Francine Décary is afflicted.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered to be biomedical wastes is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and are expected to take out more than a thousand of these each year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year - Dr. Décary describes this blood-taking program as very popular.
Many mothers are disappointed to be unable to enjoy this, since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
