If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of persecution by defamation, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to hurt anyone who dares to hold a stand contrary to theirs?
The outcome of the dispute is of little importance, the authors and editor of the book Noir Canada must spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the nearly bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will soften the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who will dare to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by beatings.
It was therefore enough for the mining woman to open her books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to not rely on public opinion and rejects requests and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a public debate by disregarding his views?
According to the vice-president, this word seems to designate only heavily paid lawyers and not all Canadians; it represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or what you don't want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does it mostly because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but based on civilized changes in arguments, and not in the context of what many people perceive as persecution-bite (following the public debate), Barrick Gold has just filed a request with respect to the authors of Noir Canada, urging them not to use this word any more).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's process is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, under many persecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a transparent and public debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right to reply.
The university world, which we belong to, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's unrelenting persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to place devices that limit this type of abusive persecution.
