What were they producing at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
Politicians and their accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, in a business manner, continuously and organized in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor ' s Office, the funds obtained in public contests were used for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and the municipalities - in their entirety some 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the treasury of the Fairal Baloldal organization and in part in the pocket of private persons.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public contests with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the charge, most of the invoices were false.
To this end they obtained the Talonaires in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunulas.
And the question that on behalf of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour by the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent to István Sides.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for his consumption, and these served as a model for the invoices he presented, among others, in the contests of the Ministry of Youth and Sport Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as in the City of Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András þri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports needed to obtain public subsidies.
During one of his study trips - Sides chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomy center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the center manager - so many people don't fit at once in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredert - was full of formal and contextual errors.
Because a guest in Badacsonytomaj town had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however the bill contained hundreds and thirty people.
But the highly fancied invoice manufacturers also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft gastronomy center. Because in the possession of books thereof - according to the information given to the Office - there were no documents on behalf of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
