Intelligent auto mimics the flight of beejorro
What would be the best method for developing technologies to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the sensors of obstacles existing in nature?
For example, beekeeping.
In an amazing project presented at the CATEEC of Japan, the beekeepers gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic direction system of cars type BR23C imitater of nature, to which they gave the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each beejorro creates its own particular oval space that actually looks much like our protective safety capsule - he explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the eyes made up of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle which immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the bees, changes the direction by turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any existing system at present, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
\"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,\" explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Laboratory of Mobility and the robot vehicle project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must be done in an open and close eyes.
However, unlike bees, the movement cannot go up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of turning wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bees to dodge other bees, here they only used the rotary motion for the auto robot and acceleration in addition to braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, meaning they have longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, nor much less the storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memories of gigabytes, no megabytes are needed.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, in ten years' time can be incorporated into serial-made models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the existing obstacles on his way.
