Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month prices and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Statistics Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to those in the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry increased by a minimum of 0.1 per cent over the month of July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), first of all due to the increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 per cent of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical material production branch (1.6 per cent).
A price decrease in the petrochemical sector (2.4 per cent) occurred in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of papermaking, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant burden within internal trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first July.
In a comparison of a 12-month period - in national sales in the processing industry - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal manufacturing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an 11 per cent increase.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, at energy and intermediate prices there were no changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
A 6.8 per cent decrease in the production of consumer goods was recorded in the branches and 1.4 per cent in the investment goods.
Export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
